ne Cixous' privileged themes: exile, war, violence (against women) and exclusion, as well as love, memory, beauty and tenderness.Neither art criticism nor a collection of critical essays, Hélène Cixous responds to these artworks as a poet, reading them as if they were poems. Written between 1985 and 2010, most of these essays are unpublished in English, or published only in rare catalogues or art books.Key FeaturesCombines poetic, theoretical and critical writing and Cixous' unique methodologyAddresses an important collection of contemporary artists, including Americans Nancy Spero and Roni Horn, the London artist Maria Chevska, the Cherokee artist Jeffrey Gibson, the filmmaker Ruth Bekermann, the French choreographer Karine Saporta and the French fashion designer Sonia Rykiel.Treats a range of media and genre: photography, painting, installations, film, choreography, fashion design  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAesthetics. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aArt, ModernxThemes, motivesx20th century. 0aArt, ModernxThemes, motivesx21st century. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArt, Moderny21st centuryxThemes, motives. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aMasó, Joana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMasó, Joana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegarra, Marta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSegarra, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864744640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074864745340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748647453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748647453/orig